(682, 6, 2, 3, '3.0 Materials for Production', '3.1 Introduction to Materials', 'By the end of the sub strand, the learner should be to:\nidentify materials used in production,\ndistinguish between metallic and non-metallic materials found in the locality,\ndescribe sustainable ways of using materials in production,\nappreciate the importance of materials in production.', 'By the end of the sub strand, the learner should be to:\nidentify materials used in production,\ndistinguish between metallic and non-metallic materials found in the locality,\ndescribe sustainable ways of using materials in production,\nappreciate the importance of materials in production.', 'The learner is guided to:\ndiscuss and present the meaning of materials used in production,\nuse print or digital media to search for information on materials used in production and share with peers,\ndiscuss the differences between metallic and non-metallic materials,\nsort out materials in the locality as either metallic or non-metallic,\nbrainstorm and present sustainable ways of using materials in production,\ndiscuss and make a presentation on the importance of materials used in production.', 'The learner is guided to:\ndiscuss and present the meaning of materials used in production,\nuse print or digital media to search for information on materials used in production and share with peers,\ndiscuss the differences between metallic and non-metallic materials,\nsort out materials in the locality as either metallic or non-metallic,\nbrainstorm and present sustainable ways of using materials in production,\ndiscuss and make a presentation on the importance of materials used in production.', '', 'Pre-Technical Studies curriculum design\nPre-Technical Studies handbook\nDigital devices such as; computers, laptops, smartphones, and tablets, among others\nMetallic and non-metallic materials\nRelevant approved textbooks and reference materials\nPhotographs and pictures\nCharts', 'Question and Answer\nObservation\nWritten Test\nPeer and Self-Assessment', '', '2026-04-12 12:35:58', '2026-04-12 12:35:58', NULL),
(683, 6, 2, 4, '3.0 Materials for Production', '3.2 Metallic Materials', 'By the end of the sub strand, the learner should be able to:\nidentify types of metallic materials used in the immediate environment,\ndescribe the physical properties of metallic materials found in the immediate environment,\nrelate metallic materials to their use in the immediate environment,\nappreciate the use of metallic materials in production.', 'By the end of the sub strand, the learner should be able to:\nidentify types of metallic materials used in the immediate environment,\ndescribe the physical properties of metallic materials found in the immediate environment,\nrelate metallic materials to their use in the immediate environment,\nappreciate the use of metallic materials in production.', 'The learner is guided to:\nuse print or digital media to search for information on metallic materials,\nprepare a checklist for identifying types of metallic materials (steel, aluminium, copper),\nperform practical activities to examine the physical properties of metallic materials (magnetism, conductivity of heat and electricity, appearance),\ndiscuss the physical properties of metallic materials,\nmatch metallic materials to their use in the immediate environment.', 'The learner is guided to:\nuse print or digital media to search for information on metallic materials,\nprepare a checklist for identifying types of metallic materials (steel, aluminium, copper),\nperform practical activities to examine the physical properties of metallic materials (magnetism, conductivity of heat and electricity, appearance),\ndiscuss the physical properties of metallic materials,\nmatch metallic materials to their use in the immediate environment.', '', 'Metallic materials (steel, aluminium, copper)\nbrochures and magazines\nDigital devices such as; computers, laptops, smartphones, and tablets, among others', 'Question and Answer\nObservation\nWritten Test\nPeer and Self-Assessment\nPractical Work', '', '2026-04-12 12:35:58', '2026-04-12 12:35:58', NULL),
(684, 6, 3, 1, '3.0 Materials for Production', '3.3 Non-Metallic Materials', 'By the end of the sub strand, the learner should be able to:\nidentify non-metallic materials found in the locality,\ncategorise non-metallic materials as either synthetic or natural,\ndescribe the physical properties of non-metallic materials found in the locality,\nrelate non-metallic materials to their uses in the locality,\nappreciate the use of non-metallic materials in production.', 'By the end of the sub strand, the learner should be able to:\nidentify non-metallic materials found in the locality,\ncategorise non-metallic materials as either synthetic or natural,\ndescribe the physical properties of non-metallic materials found in the locality,\nrelate non-metallic materials to their uses in the locality,\nappreciate the use of non-metallic materials in production.', 'The learner is guided to:\nuse print or digital media to search for information on non-metallic materials,\ndiscuss the non-metallic materials (wood, stone, plastics, paper, rubber, cement, glass, ceramics),\nsort non-metallic materials as either synthetic or natural,\nperform practical activities to examine the physical properties of non-metallic materials (color, texture, hardness, fire resistance),\ndiscuss the physical properties of non-metallic materials,\nmatch non-metallic materials to their use in the locality.', 'The learner is guided to:\nuse print or digital media to search for information on non-metallic materials,\ndiscuss the non-metallic materials (wood, stone, plastics, paper, rubber, cement, glass, ceramics),\nsort non-metallic materials as either synthetic or natural,\nperform practical activities to examine the physical properties of non-metallic materials (color, texture, hardness, fire resistance),\ndiscuss the physical properties of non-metallic materials,\nmatch non-metallic materials to their use in the locality.', '', 'Non-Metallic materials (wood, plastics, ceramic, paper, rubber, glass, cement, stone)\nbrochures and magazines\nDigital devices such as; computers, laptops, smartphones, and tablets, among others Digital devices such as; computer, laptop, smartphone, tablets among others', 'Question and Answer\nObservation\nWritten Test\nPeer and Self-Assessment\nPractical Work', '', '2026-04-12 12:35:58', '2026-04-12 12:35:58', NULL),
(685, 6, 3, 2, '4.0 Tools and Production', '4.1 Measuring and Marking Out Tools', 'By the end of the sub strand, the learner should be able to:\nidentify measuring and marking out tools used to perform tasks,\nselect measuring and marking out tools for a given task,\nuse measuring and marking out tools to perform a given task,\ncare for measuring and marking out tools to minimise damage,\nrecognise the importance of measuring and marking out tools when performing tasks.', 'By the end of the sub strand, the learner should be able to:\nidentify measuring and marking out tools used to perform tasks,\nselect measuring and marking out tools for a given task,\nuse measuring and marking out tools to perform a given task,\ncare for measuring and marking out tools to minimise damage,\nrecognise the importance of measuring and marking out tools when performing tasks.', 'The learner is guided to:\nuse visual aids and realia to identify measuring tools (tape measure, steel rule, callipers, weighing balance, stopwatch, ammeter, voltmeter) and marking out tools (divider, try-square, marking gauge, dot punch, scriber, pencil, marking knife),\nchoose the appropriate measuring and marking out tools to perform a given task,\nuse available resources to search for information on the use of measuring and marking out tools,\nperform specific tasks using measuring and marking out tools,\npractice caring for measuring and marking out tools.', 'The learner is guided to:\nuse visual aids and realia to identify measuring tools (tape measure, steel rule, callipers, weighing balance, stopwatch, ammeter, voltmeter) and marking out tools (divider, try-square, marking gauge, dot punch, scriber, pencil, marking knife),\nchoose the appropriate measuring and marking out tools to perform a given task,\nuse available resources to search for information on the use of measuring and marking out tools,\nperform specific tasks using measuring and marking out tools,\npractice caring for measuring and marking out tools.', '', 'Measuring tools (Tape measure, steel rule, callipers, weighing balance, stopwatch, ammeter, voltmeter)\nMarking out tools (divider, try-square, marking gauge, dot punch, scriber, pencil, marking knife) in the immediate environment\nbrochures and magazines', 'Question and Answer\nObservation\nWritten Test\nPeer and Self-assessment\nPractical Work', '', '2026-04-12 12:35:58', '2026-04-12 12:35:58', NULL),
(686, 6, 3, 3, '4.0 Tools and Production', '4.2 Computer Hardware', 'By the end of the sub strand the learner should be able to:\nclassify computer hardware devices in a user environment,\nuse computer hardware devices to carry out a given task,\nvalue the importance of computer hardware devices in a user environment.', 'By the end of the sub strand the learner should be able to:\nclassify computer hardware devices in a user environment,\nuse computer hardware devices to carry out a given task,\nvalue the importance of computer hardware devices in a user environment.', 'The learner is guided to:\nbrainstorm and present the meaning of the term \'computer hardware\',\nuse available resources to search for information on categories of computer hardware: input devices (keying devices, pointing devices, scanning devices, voice input devices, touch screen, digitizer, digital cameras), output devices (hardcopy and softcopy), storage devices (fixed and removable devices),\nmatch available devices to their respective categories,\nperform tasks using computer input, output, and storage devices.', 'The learner is guided to:\nbrainstorm and present the meaning of the term \'computer hardware\',\nuse available resources to search for information on categories of computer hardware: input devices (keying devices, pointing devices, scanning devices, voice input devices, touch screen, digitizer, digital cameras), output devices (hardcopy and softcopy), storage devices (fixed and removable devices),\nmatch available devices to their respective categories,\nperform tasks using computer input, output, and storage devices.', '', 'Digital devices such as; computers, laptops, smartphones, and tablets. among others.', 'Question and Answer\nObservation\nWritten Test\nPractical Work', '', '2026-04-12 12:35:58', '2026-04-12 12:35:58', NULL),
(687, 6, 3, 4, '5.0 Entrepreneurship', '5.1 Introduction to Entrepreneurship', 'By the end of the sub-strand, the learner should be able to:\nexplain the importance of entrepreneurship in the community,\ndescribe the qualities of an entrepreneur in business,\nexplore sources of business ideas for a business venture,\nappreciate the role of entrepreneurship in a community.', 'By the end of the sub-strand, the learner should be able to:\nexplain the importance of entrepreneurship in the community,\ndescribe the qualities of an entrepreneur in business,\nexplore sources of business ideas for a business venture,\nappreciate the role of entrepreneurship in a community.', 'Learner is guided to:\nbrainstorm and present the meaning of the terms \'entrepreneur\' and \'entrepreneurship\',\ndiscuss and present the importance of entrepreneurship in the community,\nuse print or digital resources to search for information on the qualities of an entrepreneur,\nconduct self-assessment on entrepreneurial qualities,\nuse available resources to search for and present the meaning and sources of business ideas,\ndiscuss the role of entrepreneurship in a community.', 'Learner is guided to:\nbrainstorm and present the meaning of the terms \'entrepreneur\' and \'entrepreneurship\',\ndiscuss and present the importance of entrepreneurship in the community,\nuse print or digital resources to search for information on the qualities of an entrepreneur,\nconduct self-assessment on entrepreneurial qualities,\nuse available resources to search for and present the meaning and sources of business ideas,\ndiscuss the role of entrepreneurship in a community.', '', 'Pre-Technical Studies curriculum design\nPre-Technical Studies handbook\nDigital devices such as; computers, laptops, smartphones, and tablets among others\nRelevant approved textbooks and reference materials\nPhotographs and pictures\nCharts', 'Question and Answer\nObservation\nWritten Test\nPeer and Self-Assessment', '', '2026-04-12 12:35:58', '2026-04-12 12:35:58', NULL),
(688, 6, 4, 1, '5.0 Entrepreneurship', '5.2 Production Unit', 'By the end of the sub strand, the learner should be able to:\nexplain the factors considered when locating a production unit,\nanalyse the factors determining the size of a production unit,\nvalue the importance of locating a production unit in a suitable area.', 'By the end of the sub strand, the learner should be able to:\nexplain the factors considered when locating a production unit,\nanalyse the factors determining the size of a production unit,\nvalue the importance of locating a production unit in a suitable area.', 'Learner is guided to:\ndiscuss the meaning of the term \'production unit\' and present it to peers,\nbrainstorm and present the factors considered when choosing the location of a production unit,\nvisit the local community to assess the factors that influenced the location of a particular production unit (posho mill, salon, barber shop, welding, cyber cafe),\nuse print or digital media to search for information on the factors that determine its size and share with peers.', 'Learner is guided to:\ndiscuss the meaning of the term \'production unit\' and present it to peers,\nbrainstorm and present the factors considered when choosing the location of a production unit,\nvisit the local community to assess the factors that influenced the location of a particular production unit (posho mill, salon, barber shop, welding, cyber cafe),\nuse print or digital media to search for information on the factors that determine its size and share with peers.', '', 'Approved textbooks\nDigital devices,\nbrochures\npictures\ncharts', 'Question and answer\nlearner\'s profile\nwritten tests\nobservation\nPeer and self-assessment', '', '2026-04-12 12:35:58', '2026-04-12 12:35:58', NULL),
(689, 6, 4, 2, '5.0 Entrepreneurship', '5.3 Financial Goals', 'By the end of the sub-strand, the learner should be able to:\nexplain the importance of setting goals in financial management,\nanalyse the factors to consider when setting financial goals,\nformulate financial goals for individual development,\nobserve financial discipline in financial management.', 'By the end of the sub-strand, the learner should be able to:\nexplain the importance of setting goals in financial management,\nanalyse the factors to consider when setting financial goals,\nformulate financial goals for individual development,\nobserve financial discipline in financial management.', 'Learner is guided to:\ndiscuss and present the meaning and importance of setting goals in financial management,\nengage with a resource person on the importance of financial discipline,\nbrainstorm and present the factors to consider when setting financial goals,\nuse print or digital media to search for information on setting financial goals,\nset Specific Measurable Achievable Realistic and Time-bound (SMART) financial goals.', 'Learner is guided to:\ndiscuss and present the meaning and importance of setting goals in financial management,\nengage with a resource person on the importance of financial discipline,\nbrainstorm and present the factors to consider when setting financial goals,\nuse print or digital media to search for information on setting financial goals,\nset Specific Measurable Achievable Realistic and Time-bound (SMART) financial goals.', '', 'Pre-Technical Studies curriculum design\nPre-Technical Studies handbook\nDigital devices such as; computers, laptops, smartphones, and tablets, among others\nRelevant approved textbooks and reference materials\nPhotographs and pictures\nCharts', 'Question and Answer\nObservation\nWritten Test\nPeer and Self-Assessment\nPractical Work', '', '2026-04-12 12:35:58', '2026-04-12 12:35:58', NULL);
INSERT INTO `sub_strand_meta` (`id`, `learning_area_id`, `strand`, `sub_strand`, `key_inquiry_qs`, `core_competencies`, `values_attit`, `pcis`, `links_to_other_areas`, `resources`, `assessment`, `created_at`) VALUES
(1, 3, '1.0 Numbers', '1.1 Whole Numbers', 'How do we read and write numbers in symbols and in words?', 'Critical thinking and problem solving: learners form different numbers by rearranging digits of a given number.', 'Unity: learners, in pairs or groups, harmoniously identify total value of digits up to millions using place value apparatus.', 'Social cohesion: learners work cohesively with peers and identify the square root of a given number as a value which when multiplied by itself results in the given number.\nSafety: learners work together to create awareness on the levels of congestion on the roads using charts and discuss how to address road safety issues.', 'Learners read and write numbers in words which is enhanced from skills in Languages.', 'Place value apparatus, number charts, number cards, multiplication tables. ICT devices: Learner digital devices (LDD), teacher digital devices (TDD), mobile phones, digital clocks, television sets, videos, cameras, projectors, radios, DVD players, CDs, scanners, internet among others.', NULL, '2026-04-11 05:31:52'),
(2, 3, '1.0 Numbers', '1.2 Multiplication', 'How do we multiply numbers?', 'Creativity and imagination: learner makes patterns involving multiplication with products not exceeding 1,000 using number cards.', 'Integrity: Learner multiplies up to a 4-digit number by a 2-digit number using skip counting and demonstrates honesty in their results.', 'Self-esteem: Learner develops confidence as they estimate products  using rounding off factors which builds self-esteem.', 'Learner estimates quantities of seeds or fertiliser required for planting different crops as learnt from Agriculture.', 'Multiplication tables. ICT devices: Learner digital devices (LDD), teacher digital devices (TDD), mobile phones, digital clocks, television sets, videos, cameras, projectors, radios, DVD players, CDs, scanners, internet among others.', NULL, '2026-04-11 05:31:52'),
(3, 3, '1.0 Numbers', '1.3 Division', 'Where is division used in real life?', 'Communication and collaboration: learner discusses with peers the relationship between multiplication and division using examples.', 'Unity: learner works together with others amicably to divide up to a 4-digit number by up to a 3-digit number and shares answers.', 'Learner divides whole numbers using digital devices or other resources as they observe safety.', 'Learner divides quantities such as ingredients for cooking as learnt from Agriculture.', 'Multiplication tables. ICT devices: Learner digital devices (LDD), teacher digital devices (TDD), mobile phones, digital clocks, television sets, videos, cameras, projectors, radios, DVD players, CDs, scanners, internet among others.', NULL, '2026-04-11 05:31:52'),
(4, 3, '1.0 Numbers', '1.4 Fractions', '1. How do we add or subtract fractions?\n2. Where is percentage used in day-to-day life?', 'Learning to learn: learner works out the reciprocal of whole numbers before solving the reciprocal of proper fractions.', 'Unity: learner works harmoniously with peers and discusses reciprocals of proper fractions.', 'Learner cohesively works together with others to calculate squares of fractions through multiplication to enhance social cohesion.', 'Learner uses fractional parts of a canvas or drawing materials to draw different patterns as learnt from Creative Arts.', 'Equivalent fraction board, circular and rectangular cut-outs, counters. ICT devices: Learner digital devices (LDD), teacher digital devices (TDD), mobile phones, digital clocks, television sets, videos, cameras, projectors, radios, DVD players, CDs, scanners, internet among others.', NULL, '2026-04-11 05:31:52'),
(5, 3, '1.0 Numbers', '1.5 Decimals', 'Where are decimals applicable in real life?', 'Communication and collaboration: learner discusses and relates place value of decimals up to ten thousandths to the number of decimal places.', 'Responsibility: learner adds decimals up to 4-decimal places using place value apparatus and shows responsibility by taking care of the apparatus.', 'Learner adds decimals up to 4-decimal places using place value apparatus and share answers or working strategies with one another as part of Peer education.', 'Learner acquires new mathematical terms as they discuss and round off decimals up to 3 decimal places as acquired from Languages.', 'Place value charts, number cards. ICT devices: Learner digital devices (LDD), teacher digital devices (TDD), mobile phones, digital clocks, television sets, videos, cameras, projectors, radios, DVD players, CDs, scanners, internet among others.', NULL, '2026-04-11 05:31:52'),
(6, 3, '1.0 Numbers', '1.6 Inequalities', 'How do we solve simple inequalities?', 'Self-efficacy: learner confidently works out simple inequalities involving one unknown.', 'Responsibility: as learner works with peers to use IT devices carefully to simplify inequalities.', 'Social cohesion: Learner works together with others harmoniously to form inequalities in one unknown to enhance social cohesion.', 'Learner uses new terms used in inequalities to enhance vocabulary in Languages.', 'Digital inequality worksheets; greater than, less than or equal to, sorting cards. ICT devices: Learner digital devices (LDD), teacher digital devices (TDD), mobile phones, digital clocks, television sets, videos, cameras, projectors, radios, DVD players, CDs, scanners, internet among others.', NULL, '2026-04-11 05:31:52'),
(7, 3, '2.0 Measurement', '2.1 Length', '1. Why do we measure distances in day-to-day life?\n2. What do we use to measure length in real life?', 'Creativity and imagination: learner sketches the circumference, diameter and radius of a circle practically.', 'Unity: learner works amicably with peers to determine lengths in centimetres and millimetres in addition, subtraction, multiplication and division and discuss the answers.', 'Learner chooses appropriate units for measuring lengths of different objects in the environment as enhanced from Environmental Education.', 'Learner handles objects with care when measuring lengths of different objects in the school compound for play activities in Creative Arts.', 'Metre rule, 1 metre sticks, tape measure. ICT devices: Learner digital devices (LDD), teacher digital devices (TDD), mobile phones, digital clocks, television sets, videos, cameras, projectors, radios, DVD players, CDs, scanners, internet among others.', NULL, '2026-04-11 05:31:52'),
(8, 3, '2.0 Measurement', '2.2 Area', 'Where is area used in real life?', 'Creativity and imagination: learner works out the area of triangles in cm2 using the relationship between a rectangle and a triangle.', 'Love: learner sketches a circle on a unit square grid and counts the full squares to estimate the area of circles and compare answers with one another.', 'Learner confidently establishes that the area of a triangle is equal to a half of the area of a rectangle or a square when the rectangle or the square is divided by a diagonal to enhance self-esteem.', 'Learner explores their environment to calculate area of different places such as play fields within the community as learnt in Social Studies.', 'Square cut-outs, 1 cm squares, 1 m squares. ICT devices: Learner digital devices (LDD), teacher digital devices (TDD), mobile phones, digital clocks, television sets, videos, cameras, projectors, radios, DVD players, CDs, scanners, internet among others.', NULL, '2026-04-11 05:31:52'),
(9, 3, '2.0 Measurement', '2.3 Capacity', '1. How can we measure capacity?\n2. Where is capacity applicable in real life?', 'Critical thinking and problem solving: learner works out the relationship between cm3,  millilitres and litres through measuring capacities practically.', 'Peace: learner works together with others harmoniously to measure capacity in millilitres and litres and agree on answers.', 'Learner changes capacity in litres to millilitres using containers from the environment as part of Environmental education.', 'Learner takes accurate measurements of liquids using different containers from the immediate environment as part of Science and Technology.', 'Tea spoons, containers of different sizes, water, sand, soil. ICT devices: Learner digital devices (LDD), teacher digital devices (TDD), mobile phones, digital clocks, television sets, videos, cameras, projectors, radios, DVD players, CDs, scanners, internet among others.', NULL, '2026-04-11 05:31:52'),
(10, 3, '2.0 Measurement', '2.4 Mass', '1. How can we measure large amounts of mass?\n2. In what situations would the tonnes be more applicable to use when measuring mass?', 'Digital literacy: learner uses digital weighing machines to measure mass of different items.', 'Integrity: learner honestly determines mass of items in kilogrammes using different operations involving addition, subtraction, multiplication and division.', 'Learner discusses with others items in the environment such as loaded lorries, whose mass may be measured in tonnes and their impact on roads as learnt in Environmental education.', 'Learner discusses with others transit trucks that carry grains in tonnes to different places as learnt in Social Studies.', 'Tea spoons, soil or sand, manual/electronic weighing machine, beam balance. ICT devices: Learner digital devices (LDD), teacher digital devices (TDD), mobile phones, digital clocks, television sets, videos, cameras, projectors, radios, DVD players, CDs, scanners, internet among others.', NULL, '2026-04-11 05:31:52'),
(11, 3, '2.0 Measurement', '2.5 Time', 'How do we read and tell time?', 'Learning to learn: learner determines time in a.m. and p.m. from digital and analogue clocks.', 'Integrity: learner observes time in various activities and is punctual.', 'Learner discusses the transit trucks that carry grains in tonnes to different places as learnt from Social Studies. Learners determine time durations of travelling using travel timetables within the country as enhanced in Citizenship.', 'Learner records time taken to perform in different games such as athletics as done in Creative Arts.', 'Analogue and digital clocks, digital watches, stopwatches. ICT devices: Learner digital devices (LDD), teacher digital devices (TDD), mobile phones, digital clocks, television sets, videos, cameras, projectors, radios, DVD players, CDs, scanners, internet among others.', NULL, '2026-04-11 05:31:52'),
(12, 3, '2.0 Measurement', '2.6 Money', 'How can you make profit in a business?', 'Communication and collaboration: Learner discusses with others the meaning of profit and loss in real-life situations and shares with peers.', 'Integrity: Learner honestly determines buying and selling prices of different items in their classroom model shop.', 'Learner discusses with others income and value added tax (VAT) as a form of tax as part of financial literacy.', 'Learner participates in making budgets for buying food at home as learnt from Agriculture.', 'Price list, classroom shop, electronic money tariff charts. ICT devices: Learner digital devices (LDD), teacher digital devices (TDD), mobile phones, digital clocks, television sets, videos, cameras, projectors, radios, DVD players, CDs, scanners, internet among others.', NULL, '2026-04-11 05:31:52'),
(13, 3, '3.0 Geometry', '3.1 Lines', 'Why do we need to draw lines?', 'Creativity and imagination: as learner bisects lines using ruler and compasses.', 'Responsibility: Learner carefully shares digital devices and other resources to draw parallel lines.', 'Learner exercises caution as they use geometrical instruments in construction of parallel lines as they observe safety measures.', 'Learner constructs lines that can be used in creative drawing as part of Creative Arts.', 'Chalkboard ruler, 30 cm ruler, straight edges. ICT devices: Learner digital devices (LDD), teacher digital devices (TDD), mobile phones, digital clocks, television sets, videos, cameras, projectors, radios, DVD players, CDs, scanners, internet among others.', NULL, '2026-04-11 05:31:52'),
(14, 3, '3.0 Geometry', '3.2 Angles', 'Where can you use angles in real life?', 'Self-efficacy: Learner confidently and practically establishes sum of the interior angles in a rectangle and triangle.', 'Unity: Learner works harmoniously with others to compare the sizes of angles.', 'Learner practically establishes the sum of angles in a triangle and rectangles from different objects in the environment as enhanced in Environmental education.', 'Learner draws lines and angles that can be used in drawing and painting in Creative Art.', 'Unit angles, protractors, rulers. ICT devices: Learner digital devices (LDD), teacher digital devices (TDD), mobile phones, digital clocks, television sets, videos, cameras, projectors, radios, DVD players, CDs, scanners, internet among others.', NULL, '2026-04-11 05:31:52'),
(15, 3, '3.0 Geometry', '3.3 3-D Objects', 'How do we use containers in daily life?', 'Creativity and imagination: Learner opens up nets of cuboids, cubes and cylinders.', 'Learner discusses with others and collect 3-D objects and safely keep them as part of their role in environmental conservation to enhance Patriotism.', 'Learner discusses with others rectangular, square and circular shapes on the nets and respect each other\'s views as part of social cohesion.', 'Learner discusses with others the differences between 3-D objects in terms of faces, edges and vertices in drawing and improves language skills.', 'Cubes, cuboids, cylinders, pyramids, spheres, cut-outs of rectangles, circles, and triangles of different sizes. ICT devices: Learner digital devices (LDD), teacher digital devices (TDD), mobile phones, digital clocks, television sets, videos, cameras, projectors, radios, DVD players, CDs, scanners, internet among others.', NULL, '2026-04-11 05:31:52'),
(16, 3, '4.0 Data Handling', '4.1 Bar Graphs', 'How can bar graphs be used in real-life situations?', 'Creativity and imagination: as learner discusses with others and collects data and organises it using pictographs.', 'Integrity: Learner piles similar objects such as match boxes vertically to honestly represent data.', 'Learner collects data on identified topic from immediate environment to address community issues as part of non-formal education.', 'Learner gathers information on any items in the environment that will enhance learning in Science and Technology.', 'Bar graph worksheets, data graph worksheets, data samples from different sources. ICT devices: Learner digital devices (LDD), teacher digital devices (TDD), mobile phones, digital clocks, television sets, videos, cameras, projectors, radios, DVD players, CDs, scanners, internet among others.', NULL, '2026-04-11 05:31:52'),
(33, 1, '1.0 Foundations of Pre-Technical Studies', '1.1 Safety on Raised Platforms', 'What risks are associated with working on raised platforms?\nHow do we stay safe when working at heights?', 'Critical thinking and problem solving: learners identify, assess and evaluate risks associated with working on raised platforms and propose appropriate safety measures.\nSelf-efficacy: learners demonstrate confidence in applying personal protective equipment and safe practices when working at heights.', 'Responsibility: learners take personal responsibility for their own safety and the safety of others when working on raised platforms.\nCare: learners show concern for the wellbeing of colleagues by following and promoting safety protocols at the workplace.', 'Safety education: learners study hazards of working at heights and apply precautionary measures including use of PPE.\nOccupational safety and health (OSH): learners connect safety on raised platforms to broader workplace health and safety standards.\nEnvironmental education: learners appreciate the importance of safe, sustainable working environments.', 'Science and Technology: learners apply concepts of forces, gravity and balance studied in Science to understand risks on raised platforms. Social Studies: learners discuss community occupations that require working at heights.', 'Photographs and charts of raised platforms (ladders, trestles, scaffolding, work-benches, ramps)\nPPE samples or pictures (helmets, harnesses, safety boots, gloves)\nPrint or digital media articles on workplace accidents\nTextbook, chalkboard, chalk', 'Oral questions: identify types of raised platforms and their associated risks.\nObservation checklist: correct demonstration of PPE use during role play.\nWritten exercise: propose safety measures for a given raised-platform scenario.', '2026-04-11 10:36:09'),
(34, 1, '1.0 Foundations of Pre-Technical Studies', '1.2 Handling Hazardous Substances', 'What hazardous substances are found in our environment?\nHow do we safely handle, store and dispose of hazardous substances?', 'Critical thinking and problem solving: learners classify hazardous substances by their properties and determine appropriate safe-handling procedures for each class.\nDigital literacy: learners use print and digital media to research safety data sheets and hazard symbols for various substances.', 'Responsibility: learners observe safety procedures when handling hazardous substances to protect themselves and the community.\nCare: learners demonstrate concern for environmental health by disposing of hazardous waste correctly.\nIntegrity: learners honestly follow prescribed safety instructions rather than taking shortcuts.', 'Safety education: learners interpret hazard warning symbols, safety labels and MSDS information on hazardous containers.\nEnvironmental education: learners discuss improper disposal of hazardous substances and its impact on the environment.\nHealth education: learners relate exposure to hazardous substances to health risks including chemical burns, poisoning and respiratory problems.', 'Science and Technology: learners apply knowledge of chemical properties (flammable, corrosive, toxic) from chemistry topics. Agriculture: learners connect safe agrochemical handling to this sub-strand.', 'Sample containers with hazard symbols (empty, safe)\nCharts showing hazard pictograms (GHS/COSHH symbols)\nSafety data sheets (printouts)\nPPE: gloves, goggles, apron pictures or samples\nTextbook, chalkboard, chalk', 'Identification exercise: match hazardous substances to their hazard class (poisonous, flammable, corrosive).\nPractical observation: evaluate correct PPE selection and handling technique during simulated activity.\nWritten quiz: interpret safety symbols and state precautions for a listed hazardous substance.', '2026-04-11 10:36:09'),
(35, 1, '1.0 Foundations of Pre-Technical Studies', '1.3 Self-Exploration and Career Development', 'What are my talents and abilities?\nHow do my talents relate to career pathways in Pre-Technical Studies?', 'Self-efficacy: learners reflect on personal talents and abilities and develop confidence in pursuing relevant career pathways.\nCommunication and collaboration: learners discuss career options in groups, listen to resource persons and present findings to the class.\nCitizenship: learners understand how individual talents contribute to national development and the economy.', 'Respect: learners appreciate the diverse talents and abilities of their peers and treat all career pathways with equal value.\nResponsibility: learners commit to nurturing their talents and making informed career decisions.\nUnity: learners collaborate in identifying shared talents and supporting each other\'s aspirations.', 'Career guidance and counselling: learners map personal talents and abilities to Pre-Technical Studies career pathways (construction, manufacturing, ICT, entrepreneurship).\nLife skills education: learners develop self-awareness, goal-setting and decision-making skills related to career choices.\nCitizenship education: learners appreciate how technical careers contribute to the social and economic development of Kenya.', 'Social Studies: learners connect career exploration to the study of the economy and occupational sectors in Kenya. Life Skills: values of self-awareness and goal-setting are reinforced.', 'Career pathway charts and posters for Pre-Technical Studies fields\nGuest speaker / resource person (artisan, technician, entrepreneur)\nNewspaper and magazine articles on technical careers\nTextbook, chalkboard, chalk', 'Personal reflection activity: learners write a brief description of two personal talents and a corresponding career pathway.\nGroup presentation: present and justify their chosen career pathways to the class.\nOral question and answer: relate specific talents to Pre-Technical Studies career opportunities.', '2026-04-11 10:36:09'),
(36, 1, '2.0 Communication in Pre-Technical Studies', '2.1 Oblique Projection', 'What is oblique projection?\nHow do we use oblique projection to communicate technical ideas?', 'Creativity and imagination: learners produce neat oblique projection drawings of given objects, applying correct angles, proportions and line types.\nCritical thinking and problem solving: learners interpret oblique drawings to visualise three-dimensional objects and solve spatial problems.', 'Responsibility: learners take care of drawing tools and produce accurate, tidy work.\nIntegrity: learners present original drawings and acknowledge sources of reference.', 'Education for sustainable development (ESD): learners use drawing skills to design and communicate ideas for sustainable building and product design.\nICT integration: learners use digital drawing tools where available to create oblique projection drawings.\nInnovation and creativity: learners apply oblique projection to communicate innovative design ideas.', 'Mathematics: learners apply measurement, scale and geometric concepts when constructing oblique drawings. Art and Craft: learners transfer spatial visualisation and drawing skills from Art.', 'Drawing boards, T-squares, set squares, compasses\nDrawing pencils (H, HB, 2H), erasers, rulers\nProtractors and drawing paper / graph paper\nChalkboard diagrams and model objects\nTextbook', 'Practical drawing task: produce a neat oblique projection drawing of a given simple object.\nOral questions: identify and explain the angles and proportions used in oblique projection.\nPeer assessment: evaluate a classmate\'s drawing against given criteria (accuracy, neatness, labelling).', '2026-04-11 10:36:09'),
(37, 1, '2.0 Communication in Pre-Technical Studies', '2.2 Visual Programming', 'What is visual programming?\nHow do we use visual programming to solve problems?', 'Digital literacy: learners use block-based visual programming environments (e.g., Scratch, MIT App Inventor) to create simple programs and animations.\nCritical thinking and problem solving: learners design, test and debug visual programs to solve given problems.\nCreativity and imagination: learners create original animations, stories or games using visual programming tools.', 'Responsibility: learners handle ICT equipment with care and follow acceptable use policies.\nIntegrity: learners produce original programs and give credit for shared code resources.', 'ICT integration: learners apply digital literacy skills through hands-on use of visual programming software.\nInnovation and creativity: learners use computational thinking to design creative solutions to everyday problems.\nLife skills education: learners develop logical sequencing, persistence and collaborative problem-solving skills through programming.', 'Mathematics: learners apply sequencing, logic and geometry concepts in programming tasks. Computer Studies: visual programming concepts form a bridge to text-based programming introduced in Computer Studies.', 'Computer laboratory or tablets with Scratch / block-based IDE installed\nProjector or television for demonstration\nPrinted Scratch activity cards / worksheets\nTextbook, chalkboard', 'Practical task: create a visual program that performs a specified sequence of actions.\nOral explanation: describe the logic and sequence of their program to the class.\nPortfolio: save and present a completed visual program project with a brief description.', '2026-04-11 10:36:09'),
(38, 1, '3.0 Materials for Production', '3.1 Wood', 'What types of wood are used in production?\nHow do we select and prepare wood for various production tasks?', 'Critical thinking and problem solving: learners evaluate different wood types based on properties such as hardness, grain and durability, then select the most appropriate for a given task.\nCreativity and imagination: learners design and plan wood-based products that meet specified requirements.', 'Responsibility: learners handle wood and woodworking tools safely, following all prescribed safety procedures.\nCare: learners demonstrate respect for natural resources by using wood economically and avoiding wastage.\nPatriotism: learners appreciate local Kenyan wood species and promote sustainable use of forest resources.', 'Environmental education: learners discuss sustainable timber harvesting, afforestation and the impact of deforestation on the environment.\nESD: learners relate responsible use of wood to sustainable production and consumption practices.\nSafety education: learners apply safe tool and material handling practices when working with wood.', 'Science and Technology: learners apply knowledge of material properties from the topic on materials in Science. Agriculture and Nutrition: learners link tree farming to wood availability and sustainable land use.', 'Wood samples: softwood (e.g., cypress, pine) and hardwood (e.g., mahogany, mvuli)\nMeasuring tape, ruler, try-square\nChalkboard charts on wood types and properties\nTextbook', 'Identification exercise: classify given wood samples into softwood or hardwood and justify the choice.\nOral questions: describe the properties and uses of specified wood types.\nShort written test: explain how to select appropriate wood for a given production task.', '2026-04-11 10:36:09'),
(39, 1, '3.0 Materials for Production', '3.2 Handling Waste Materials', 'What waste materials are generated in production activities?\nHow can we reduce, reuse and recycle waste materials in Pre-Technical Studies?', 'Citizenship: learners take collective responsibility for waste management and promote environmentally responsible production practices in school and community.\nCritical thinking and problem solving: learners identify categories of waste generated in production workshops and propose effective waste-reduction strategies.', 'Responsibility: learners dispose of production waste correctly and follow workshop waste-management procedures.\nCare: learners demonstrate concern for the environment by minimising waste and recycling usable materials.\nPatriotism: learners contribute to a clean, safe community environment by practising responsible waste disposal.', 'Environmental education: learners study the impact of waste on the environment and propose sustainable waste management solutions (reduce, reuse, recycle).\nESD: learners relate responsible waste handling to sustainable production, consumption and the Green Economy.\nHealth education: learners discuss health hazards of improper waste disposal in production environments.', 'Science and Technology: learners apply knowledge of biodegradable and non-biodegradable materials from Science. Agriculture: composting of biodegradable waste links to Agriculture lessons.', 'Waste material samples (wood shavings, metal offcuts, plastic scraps, paper)\nWaste sorting bins (labelled: organic, recyclable, hazardous, general)\nCharts on waste classification and the 3R hierarchy\nTextbook, chalkboard', 'Sorting activity: correctly categorise given waste materials into appropriate disposal groups.\nGroup discussion report: present a proposed waste-management plan for the school workshop.\nOral questions: explain the environmental impact of improper waste disposal and suggest remedies.', '2026-04-11 10:36:09'),
(40, 1, '4.0 Tools and Production', '4.1 Holding Tools', 'What are holding tools?\nHow do we select and safely use holding tools in production tasks?', 'Critical thinking and problem solving: learners select the most appropriate holding tool for a given material and task, justifying their choices based on tool function and material properties.\nSelf-efficacy: learners demonstrate correct and confident use of holding tools during practical activities.', 'Responsibility: learners use, clean and store holding tools correctly to prolong tool life and prevent accidents.\nCare: learners show concern for peers by working safely and observing workshop rules when using holding tools.\nIntegrity: learners honestly report any damage to tools rather than concealing it.', 'Safety education: learners identify hazards associated with incorrect use of holding tools and apply safe operating procedures.\nOccupational safety and health (OSH): learners relate proper tool use to workplace injury prevention.\nCareer guidance: learners connect correct use of hand tools to careers in carpentry, welding and metal fabrication.', 'Science and Technology: learners apply concepts of force and mechanical advantage from Science when selecting and using tools. Mathematics: learners use measurement skills when setting up work pieces in vices and clamps.', 'Holding tools: bench vice, G-clamp, sash clamp, hand vice, pliers (flat-nose, round-nose, combination)\nWork bench\nSafety charts for tool use\nTextbook, chalkboard', 'Identification test: name given holding tools and state their specific uses.\nPractical demonstration: correctly set up a work piece in a vice or clamp and explain the technique used.\nOral questions: describe safety procedures to observe when using a specified holding tool.', '2026-04-11 10:36:09'),
(41, 1, '4.0 Tools and Production', '4.2 Driving Tools', 'What are driving tools?\nHow do we select and safely use driving tools in production activities?', 'Critical thinking and problem solving: learners evaluate different driving tools (hammers, mallets, screwdrivers, wrenches) to determine the most suitable tool for a given fastening task.\nSelf-efficacy: learners confidently demonstrate correct grip, posture and technique when using driving tools on practical tasks.', 'Responsibility: learners maintain driving tools in good working condition and store them correctly after use.\nCare: learners observe safety rules that protect themselves and their peers from tool-related injuries.\nIntegrity: learners report any defective or damaged tools immediately to prevent accidents.', 'Safety education: learners identify hazards of using damaged or incorrectly selected driving tools and describe precautions.\nOSH: learners apply occupational health and safety standards to driving-tool use in the workshop.\nCareer guidance: learners relate driving-tool skills to careers in construction, motor vehicle mechanics and manufacturing.', 'Science and Technology: learners apply concepts of force, torque and leverage from Physics when using hammers and wrenches. Technical Drawing: fastener symbols studied in drawing relate to the fasteners driven in this sub-strand.', 'Driving tools: claw hammer, mallet, cross-pein hammer, flat-head and cross-head screwdrivers, adjustable wrench, spanner set\nWork bench, nails, screws, bolts and nuts (samples)\nSafety charts\nTextbook, chalkboard', 'Identification: name given driving tools and state their correct use.\nPractical task: drive a nail or fix a screw into a work piece using correct technique and posture.\nOral questions: explain safety precautions to observe when using a hammer or screwdriver.', '2026-04-11 10:36:09'),
(42, 1, '4.0 Tools and Production', '4.3 Project', 'How do we apply Pre-Technical Studies skills to design and make a useful product?\nWhat makes a project successful?', 'Creativity and imagination: learners design original, functional products that address real needs using materials and tools studied in the strand.\nCritical thinking and problem solving: learners evaluate their designs, identify limitations and propose improvements based on testing outcomes.\nCommunication and collaboration: learners work in groups to plan, assign roles, make and present their project, communicating progress and challenges throughout.\nSelf-efficacy: learners demonstrate the confidence and persistence to carry a project from idea to finished product.', 'Responsibility: learners take ownership of their project, meeting timelines and producing quality work.\nIntegrity: learners acknowledge the contributions of group members and present honest evaluations of their finished product.\nCare: learners handle tools and materials safely throughout the project and tidy the workspace after use.', 'Innovation and creativity: learners apply the design process to produce innovative, locally-relevant products.\nCareer guidance: project work introduces learners to the professional cycle of design, production and evaluation used in technical careers.\nESD: learners design products that consider material economy, environment impact and community value.\nEntrepreneurship: learners consider the market potential and costing of their project product.', 'Mathematics: learners apply measurement, scale, area and cost calculations to their project. Science: material properties and forces inform design and construction decisions. Business Studies/Entrepreneurship: costing and pricing of the project output.', 'Materials appropriate to the project (wood, metal, plastic, reclaimed materials)\nHolding and driving tools studied in Strand 4\nMeasuring tools (ruler, tape measure, try-square)\nProject planning worksheet\nTextbook, chalkboard', 'Project portfolio/logbook: design brief, annotated sketch, materials list and process diary.\nFinished product evaluation: assess product against design criteria (functionality, finish, safety, environmental consideration).\nOral presentation: explain design decisions, challenges faced and how they were resolved.', '2026-04-11 10:36:09'),
(43, 1, '5.0 Entrepreneurship', '5.1 Financial Services', 'What financial services are available to support small businesses?\nHow do we use financial services to grow a business?', 'Self-efficacy: learners develop confidence in managing personal finances and making informed decisions about savings, credit and investment.\nCritical thinking and problem solving: learners compare available financial services (bank accounts, mobile money, SACCOs, microfinance) and evaluate their suitability for different business needs.\nDigital literacy: learners explore mobile-banking and digital-payment platforms as business tools.', 'Integrity: learners appreciate the importance of honest financial record-keeping, repaying loans and honouring financial commitments.\nResponsibility: learners demonstrate responsible borrowing and saving behaviour.\nSocial justice: learners discuss equitable access to financial services and the role of cooperative societies in empowering communities.', 'Financial literacy: learners study savings, credit, insurance, mobile money and investment as tools for business growth.\nLife skills education: learners develop decision-making skills related to personal and business financial management.\nCareer guidance: learners explore careers in banking, microfinance and financial technology (FinTech).', 'Mathematics: learners apply percentage, ratio and interest calculations to financial service scenarios. Social Studies: learners relate financial systems to the Kenyan economy studied in Social Studies.', 'Charts showing types of financial institutions (banks, SACCOs, microfinance, mobile money)\nSample bank account opening forms and loan application forms\nMobile banking demonstration (teacher phone / video)\nTextbook, chalkboard', 'Case study analysis: recommend the most appropriate financial service for a described small business situation and justify the choice.\nOral questions: explain how a SACCO or bank account supports entrepreneurship.\nShort written test: calculate simple interest on a loan or savings scenario.', '2026-04-11 10:36:09'),
(44, 1, '5.0 Entrepreneurship', '5.2 Government and Business', 'What is the role of the government in business?\nHow do government policies and regulations affect entrepreneurs?', 'Critical thinking and problem solving: learners analyse the impact of government taxation, licensing and regulation on small businesses and propose how entrepreneurs can operate within the law.\nCitizenship: learners appreciate the contribution of taxes to public services and the importance of legal business registration.\nCommunication and collaboration: learners debate government roles in supporting and regulating business in group discussions.', 'Patriotism: learners appreciate that taxes paid by businesses fund public services that benefit all Kenyans.\nIntegrity: learners commit to ethical business practices including accurate financial reporting, tax compliance and fair trade.\nResponsibility: learners understand the civic responsibility to register businesses and pay taxes as required by law.\nSocial justice: learners discuss how government regulation can protect consumers, employees and the environment.', 'Citizenship education: learners study the legal and civic obligations of business operators in Kenya, including business licensing and tax compliance.\nFinancial literacy: learners understand the role of taxation, government levies and business facilitation funds.\nCareer guidance: learners explore careers in government regulatory bodies (KRA, KEBS, county business offices).', 'Social Studies: learners relate government functions and devolution to business regulation at national and county level. Mathematics: learners apply percentage calculations when computing VAT, import duty and income tax.', 'Charts: types of business registrations, licences and tax obligations in Kenya\nSample business permit, NSSF/NHIF registration forms (copies)\nKRA iTax awareness poster / video\nTextbook, chalkboard', 'Discussion task: explain two ways in which government policies support or constrain small businesses in Kenya.\nOral questions: describe the steps to legally register a small business and why registration matters.\nWritten exercise: list three government obligations of a small business owner and explain the consequence of non-compliance.', '2026-04-11 10:36:09'),
(45, 1, '5.0 Entrepreneurship', '5.3 Business Plan', 'What is a business plan?\nHow do we develop a business plan for a Pre-Technical Studies enterprise?', 'Critical thinking and problem solving: learners analyse market needs and competition, then design a viable business plan that addresses a real community opportunity.\nCreativity and imagination: learners develop innovative business ideas and create compelling, original business plans.\nSelf-efficacy: learners develop confidence in their entrepreneurial ability through the process of planning and presenting a business idea.\nCommunication and collaboration: learners work in groups to research, draft and pitch their business plan to peers or invited evaluators.', 'Integrity: learners produce realistic, accurate financial projections and honestly assess the strengths and weaknesses of their business idea.\nResponsibility: learners take ownership of the planning process, meet deadlines and produce a well-organised plan.\nSocial justice: learners consider the social and environmental impact of their proposed business on the community.\nUnity: learners collaborate respectfully, valuing each team member\'s contribution to the business plan.', 'Entrepreneurship education: learners apply the full entrepreneurial process — idea generation, market research, financial planning, marketing and evaluation — in developing their business plan.\nCareer guidance: business plan development prepares learners for self-employment and entrepreneurial careers in technical fields.\nESD: learners incorporate environmental sustainability considerations into their business plan.\nLife skills education: learners develop research, writing, financial literacy and presentation skills through the business planning process.', 'Mathematics: learners apply cost calculations, profit/loss, break-even analysis and budgeting skills. English/Communication: learners use writing and presentation skills from Language lessons to prepare and pitch the plan.', 'Business plan template / worksheet\nSample completed business plans (simple, appropriate level)\nCharts: components of a business plan (executive summary, market analysis, operations, financials, marketing)\nTextbook, chalkboard', 'Business plan document: evaluate completeness, realism and viability of the plan against a rubric (executive summary, market analysis, financial plan, marketing strategy).\nPitch presentation: assess clarity, confidence and ability to answer questions about the plan.\nPeer review: structured peer feedback on one another\'s business plans using a provided checklist.', '2026-04-11 10:36:09'),
(105, 6, '1.0 Foundations of Pre-Technical Studies', '1.1 Introduction to Pre-Technical Studies', 'Why is Pre-Technical Studies important in day-to-day life?', 'Communication and Collaboration: learner develops writing, speaking, listening, and teamwork skills when discussing, and presenting on the role of Pre-Technical Studies., Critical Thinking and Problem Solving: learner develops open-mindedness and creativity skills when brainstorming on Pre-Technical Studies as a learning area.', 'Unity: learner displays team spirit and collaboration with others when discussing and presenting the role of Pre-Technical Studies in day-to-day life., Respect: learner displays tolerance for others\' opinions when debating on the role of Pre-Technical Studies in day-to-day life.', 'Social Cohesion is enhanced when debating on the role of Pre-Technical Studies.', 'The learner is able to relate career to trade and economic activities in Social Studies.', 'Pre-Technical Studies curriculum design\nPre-Technical Studies handbook\nDigital devices such as; computers laptops, smartphones, and tablets among others\nRelevant approved textbooks and reference materials\nPhotographs and pictures\nCharts', 'Question and Answer\nObservation\nWritten Test\nPractical Work\nPeer and Self-Assessment', '2026-04-12 12:35:58'),
(106, 6, '1.0 Foundations of Pre-Technical Studies', '1.2 Safety in the Immediate Environment', '1. Why is safety in the immediate environment important?\n2. How can online threats be safeguarded against?', 'Learning to Learn: learner develops skills of sharing learnt knowledge when taking turns with peers to share ideas on safety for self and others in the immediate environment., Digital Literacy: learner develops skills of interacting with technology when searching for information on potential hazards to personal safety in the immediate environment.', 'Respect: learner appreciates diverse opinions when sharing information with peers on the online threats., Responsibility: learner engages in assigned roles when role playing on safety for self and others in the immediate environment.', 'Disaster Risk Reduction: learner observes safety when role playing on safety of self and others in the immediate environment., Safety and Security: safety awareness on threats such as falls, road crashes, slips, trips, and fires is enhanced when sharing ideas and practices on how to protect self and others from threats in the immediate environment.', 'Integrated Science when the learner observes safety when working in a science laboratory.', 'Workshop attires such as; overcoats, aprons, shoes, and goggles, among others.\nCareer brochures, career magazines\nDigital devices such as; computers, laptops, smartphones, and tablets, among others', 'Question and Answer\nObservation\nWritten Test\nPractical Work\nPeer and Self-Assessment', '2026-04-12 12:35:58'),
(107, 6, '1.0 Foundations of Pre-Technical Studies', '1.3 Computer Concepts', '1. Why are computers classified differently?\n2. How are computers used in day-to-day life?', 'Critical Thinking and Problem Solving: learner develops interpretation and inference skills while brainstorming on the meaning of the terms; computer, data, and information., Communication and Collaboration: learner develops speaking, listening, and teamwork skills when discussing the classification of computers in a user environment.', 'Responsibility: learner shows accountability by caring for the print or digital media when interacting with different types of computers in the user environment to perform tasks., Peace: learner displays patience with peers when discussing the classification of computers.', '', '', 'Course books,\nComputer user manuals,\nInternet,\nVideo clips\nDigital devices such as; computers, laptops, smart phones, tablets among others.', 'Question and Answer\nObservation\nWritten Test\nPractical Work\nPeer and Self-Assessment', '2026-04-12 12:35:58'),
(108, 6, '2.0 Communication in Pre-Technical Studies', '2.1 Introduction to Drawing', 'How are drawings used in technical communication?', 'Communication and Collaboration: the learner acquires speaking, listening and teamwork skills when brainstorming on the meaning of the terms \'technical drawing\' and \'artistic drawing\'., Digital Literacy: learner develops the skill of interacting with technology when using online resources to search for information on artistic and technical drawing.', 'Respect: learner demonstrates etiquette during discussion of basic symbols and abbreviations used in drawing., Responsibility: learner demonstrates accountability when using visual aids to search for information on the types of lines and their application in drawing.', 'Safety and Security: the learner develops online safety when using online resources to search for information on artistic and technical drawing.', '', 'Drawing charts\nDrawing papers/books\nbrochures and magazines\nGeometrical set', 'Question and Answer\nObservation\nWritten Test\nPeer and Self-Assessment', '2026-04-12 12:35:58'),
(109, 6, '2.0 Communication in Pre-Technical Studies', '2.2 Free-hand sketching', 'Why is free-hand sketching important?', 'Communication and Collaboration: learner acquires speaking, listening, and teamwork skills when discussing the meaning of free-hand sketching as used in Pre-Technical Studies., Digital Literacy: learner develops the skill of interacting with technology when using digital media to observe how free-hand sketches express artistic ideas in different career fields.', 'Respect: learner demonstrates etiquette during discussion of the meaning of free-hand sketching as used in Pre-Technical Studies, Responsibility: learner demonstrates accountability when using digital media, to observe how free-hand sketches express artistic ideas in different career fields.', 'Safety and Security: learner develops online safety skills when using digital media to observe how free hand sketches express artistic ideas in different career fields.', 'Creative arts: learner enhances skill of artistic drawing when using pencils and drawing papers to create lines.', 'Drawing charts\nDrawing pencils,\nDrawing papers/books', 'Checklist\nObservation\nPeer and self-assessment', '2026-04-12 12:35:58'),
(110, 6, '2.0 Communication in Pre-Technical Studies', '2.3 ICT Tools in Communication', 'How are ICT tools used in communication?', 'Communication and Collaboration: learner acquires speaking, writing, listening, and teamwork skills while brainstorming and presenting on the meaning and importance of ICT tools in communication., Learning to Learn: learner acquires skills of organizing own learning and collaborating with others when using print or digital media to search for information on ICT tools used in communication., Digital Literacy: learner develops the skill of interacting with technology when using print or digital media to search for information on ICT tools used in communication.', 'Respect, Responsibility', 'Mental Health', 'English', 'Digital devices such as; computers, laptops, smartphones, and tablets, among others.\nInternet\nSocial media applications', 'Question and Answer\nObservation\nWritten Test\nPeer and Self-Assessment', '2026-04-12 12:35:58'),
(111, 6, '3.0 Materials for Production', '3.1 Introduction to Materials', 'How are materials used sustainably?', 'Self-efficacy, Critical Thinking and Problem Solving', 'Responsibility, Peace', 'Environmental Education', '', 'Pre-Technical Studies curriculum design\nPre-Technical Studies handbook\nDigital devices such as; computers, laptops, smartphones, and tablets, among others\nMetallic and non-metallic materials\nRelevant approved textbooks and reference materials\nPhotographs and pictures\nCharts', 'Question and Answer\nObservation\nWritten Test\nPeer and Self-Assessment', '2026-04-12 12:35:58'),
(112, 6, '3.0 Materials for Production', '3.2 Metallic Materials', 'How are metallic materials used in day-to-day life?', 'Digital Literacy, Communication and Collaboration', 'Unity, Responsibility', 'Peer Education and Mentorship', 'Integrated Science', 'Metallic materials (steel, aluminium, copper)\nbrochures and magazines\nDigital devices such as; computers, laptops, smartphones, and tablets, among others', 'Question and Answer\nObservation\nWritten Test\nPeer and Self-Assessment\nPractical Work', '2026-04-12 12:35:58');
INSERT INTO `sub_strand_meta` (`id`, `learning_area_id`, `strand`, `sub_strand`, `key_inquiry_qs`, `core_competencies`, `values_attit`, `pcis`, `links_to_other_areas`, `resources`, `assessment`, `created_at`) VALUES
(113, 6, '3.0 Materials for Production', '3.3 Non-Metallic Materials', 'Why are non-metallic materials important?', 'Critical Thinking and Problem Solving, Creativity and Imagination', 'Peace, Unity', 'Environmental Education', 'Social Studies', 'Non-Metallic materials (wood, plastics, ceramic, paper, rubber, glass, cement, stone)\nbrochures and magazines\nDigital devices such as; computers, laptops, smartphones, and tablets, among others Digital devices such as; computer, laptop, smartphone, tablets among others', 'Question and Answer\nObservation\nWritten Test\nPeer and Self-Assessment\nPractical Work', '2026-04-12 12:35:58'),
(114, 6, '4.0 Tools and Production', '4.1 Measuring and Marking Out Tools', 'Why are measuring and marking out tools important in day-to-day life?\nHow are measuring and marking out tools used when performing tasks?', 'Critical Thinking and Problem Solving, Self-efficacy', 'Respect', 'Disaster Risk Reduction: learner avoids situations that can lead to injuries when caring for measuring and marking out tools in the immediate environment.', 'Mathematics: learner enhances the skill of measurement when performing specific tasks using measuring and marking out tools.', 'Measuring tools (Tape measure, steel rule, callipers, weighing balance, stopwatch, ammeter, voltmeter)\nMarking out tools (divider, try-square, marking gauge, dot punch, scriber, pencil, marking knife) in the immediate environment\nbrochures and magazines', 'Question and Answer\nObservation\nWritten Test\nPeer and Self-assessment\nPractical Work', '2026-04-12 12:35:58'),
(115, 6, '4.0 Tools and Production', '4.2 Computer Hardware', 'How is computer hardware used?', 'Communication and Collaboration: learner acquires speaking, writing, listening, and teamwork skills when brainstorming and presenting on the meaning of the term \'computer hardware\'., Critical Thinking and Problem Solving: learner develops skills of interpretation and inference when categorising computer hardware.', 'Peace: learner displays tolerance when performing tasks using computer hardware., Responsibility: learner shows accountability when using available resources to search for information on categories of computer hardware.', 'Peer Education and Mentorship: learner enhances leadership skills when discussing the categories of computer hardware devices in a user environment.', 'Integrated Science: learner enhances skills of connecting electric devices when connecting hardware devices.', 'Digital devices such as; computers, laptops, smartphones, and tablets. among others.', 'Question and Answer\nObservation\nWritten Test\nPractical Work', '2026-04-12 12:35:58'),
(116, 6, '5.0 Entrepreneurship', '5.1 Introduction to Entrepreneurship', 'Why is entrepreneurship important in the community?\nWhat are the qualities of an entrepreneur?', 'Communication and Collaboration: learner acquires speaking, writing, listening, and teamwork skills when brainstorming and presenting on the meaning of the terms \'entrepreneur\' and \'entrepreneurship\'., Critical Thinking and Problem Solving: learner acquires evaluation and decision-making skills when conducting a self-assessment on entrepreneurial qualities.', 'Unity: learner displays team spirit when discussing and presenting the importance of entrepreneurship to an individual and community., Responsibility: learner engages in the use of available resources to search for and present the meaning and sources of business ideas.', 'Financial Literacy: learner develops entrepreneurial skills when conducting self-assessment on entrepreneurial qualities.', 'Social Studies: learner enhances knowledge on trading activities when discussing the role of entrepreneurship in a community.', 'Pre-Technical Studies curriculum design\nPre-Technical Studies handbook\nDigital devices such as; computers, laptops, smartphones, and tablets among others\nRelevant approved textbooks and reference materials\nPhotographs and pictures\nCharts', 'Question and Answer\nObservation\nWritten Test\nPeer and Self-Assessment', '2026-04-12 12:35:58'),
(117, 6, '5.0 Entrepreneurship', '5.2 Production Unit', 'How is the size of a production unit determined?', 'Communication and Collaboration: learner acquires speaking, writing, listening, and teamwork skills when discussing and presenting the meaning of the term \'production unit\'., Critical Thinking and Problem Solving: learner acquires interpretation and inference skills when visiting the local community to assess the factors that influenced the location of a particular production unit.', 'Responsibility: learner shows accountability when using print or digital media to search for information on the factors that determine its size and share with peers.', 'Financial Literacy: learner develops entrepreneurial skills when brainstorming and presenting the factors considered when choosing the location of a production unit.', 'Social Studies: learner enhances knowledge on trade when brainstorming on factors considered when choosing the location of a production unit.', 'Approved textbooks\nDigital devices,\nbrochures\npictures\ncharts', 'Question and answer\nlearner\'s profile\nwritten tests\nobservation\nPeer and self-assessment', '2026-04-12 12:35:58'),
(118, 6, '5.0 Entrepreneurship', '5.3 Financial Goals', 'Why is it important to set financial goals?\nWhat are the factors to consider when setting financial goals?', 'Self-efficacy: learner acquires the skill of task execution when setting SMART financial goals., Critical Thinking and Problem Solving: learner acquires interpretation and inference skills when brainstorming on the factors to consider when setting financial goals.', 'Responsibility: learner engages in assigned roles and duties when discussing and presenting on the meaning and importance of goal setting as used in financial management., Respect: learner shows regard for the input of every member when brainstorming and presenting on the factors to consider when setting financial goals.', 'Financial Literacy: learner acquires financial skills when setting SMART financial goals.', 'Social Studies: learner enhances skills of personal goal setting when setting SMART financial goals.', 'Pre-Technical Studies curriculum design\nPre-Technical Studies handbook\nDigital devices such as; computers, laptops, smartphones, and tablets, among others\nRelevant approved textbooks and reference materials\nPhotographs and pictures\nCharts', 'Question and Answer\nObservation\nWritten Test\nPeer and Self-Assessment\nPractical Work', '2026-04-12 12:35:58');
